      {
        "number": 2,
        "title": "The great purge — dismantling centuries of idolatry from inside out",
        "range": "23:4-20",
        "excerpt": "He did away with the idolatrous priests whom the kings of Judah had appointed to burn incense in the high places... also those who burned incense to Baal, to the sun and to the moon and to the constellations and to all the host of heaven.",
        "body": "The seventeen-verse purge inventory is the most exhaustive cultic-reform catalogue in the Old Testament. What makes it theologically significant is not merely its scope but its revelatory function: by listing what Josiah removed, the narrator exposes what had been present. Asherah poles in the temple courts (23:6-7), altars to the host of heaven on Ahaz's palace roof and in the inner courts of the LORD's house (23:12), cult prostitute quarters inside the temple precincts where women wove hangings for Asherah (23:7), horses and chariots dedicated to the sun at the temple entrance (23:11). The idolatry was not popular religion happening at a safe distance from the official cult — it had colonized the temple itself.\n\nThe sociological reality behind this list is that syncretism is always institutional before it is personal. The idolatrous priests ('kamarim,' 23:5, a term used only for illegitimate pagan priests, never Levitical priests) had been appointed by the kings of Judah — the state had sponsored the corruption. Manasseh's reign (2 Kings 21:1-9) had been a systematic program of paganization so thorough that the narrator compares him to the nations God had cast out before Israel (21:2). The objects Josiah burns in 23:4-12 are the institutional legacy of that royal apostasy. No private reform could address structures established by royal policy; only a king could undo what kings had done.\n\nThe extension to Bethel and Samaria (23:15-20) is the chapter's most historically remarkable move. Bethel had not been under Judean authority since the kingdom divided circa 930 BC. That Josiah can enter Assyrian provincial territory and slaughter priests on their altars signals the collapse of Assyrian hegemony in the west (Nineveh fell to Babylon in 612 BC, and Assyrian power was already fragmenting in 621 BC). The Deuteronomistic historian uses this political window to make a theological point: Jeroboam's foundational sin — the golden calves at Bethel and Dan (1 Kings 12:28-29) — had defined the northern kingdom's apostasy for its entire existence ('the sin of Jeroboam' is the narrator's refrain throughout 1-2 Kings for every northern king). Josiah's destruction of the Bethel altar is nothing less than the undoing of the schism's theological catastrophe.\n\nThe fulfillment of the man of God's prophecy (23:16, referencing 1 Kings 13:2) deserves sustained attention. The prophecy was specific: a son named Josiah would be born to David's house, would burn human bones on the Bethel altar, and would defile it. The prophecy was spoken to Jeroboam himself at the moment of the altar's dedication — roughly 300 years before its fulfillment. Peter Davids and other scholars of prophetic fulfillment have noted that this is one of Scripture's most precise named-fulfillments: a personal name, a specific action, a specific place, and a specific altar, all confirmed three centuries later. For the Deuteronomistic historian, this is the signature of a God whose word is not contingent on human historical decisions.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kamar* (idolatrous priest) — used pejoratively only for illegitimate cult personnel, never Levitical priests. *Tame* (defile) — to render ritually impure; Josiah's strategy of defiling high places with human bones (corpse-impurity, Numbers 19:11-13) renders them permanently unusable. *Saraph* (burn) — to consume completely; the word for the burning of sacrifices but here turned against idolatrous objects."
      },
      {
        "number": 3,
        "title": "The Passover — recovering Israel's redemption identity",
        "range": "23:21-24",
        "excerpt": "Surely such a Passover had not been celebrated from the days of the judges who judged Israel, nor in all the days of the kings of Israel and of the kings of Judah.",
        "body": "The Passover of 621 BC is not the reform's appendix — it is its theological climax. The destruction of idolatry (23:4-20) removed the false; the Passover reinstates the true. And what it reinstates is not a cultic ceremony but a founding narrative: Israel is constituted as a people by the exodus, and the Passover is the annual re-enactment of that constituting event. To celebrate Passover as written in the book of the covenant (23:21) is to re-anchor the nation in its definitive identity as a people delivered by divine initiative, not merely a nation obligated to keep moral rules.\n\nThe narrator's comparison — 'not since the days of the judges' (23:22) — is pregnant with significance. The judges era was the period of cyclical apostasy and deliverance described in the book of Judges, but it was also the period closest to the Sinai covenant in historical memory, before the monarchy introduced its own distortions. To compare Josiah's Passover to that era is to suggest that the reform has reached back past the entire corrupted monarchy to recover something constitutionally foundational. The Chronicler's parallel account (2 Chronicles 35:1-19) adds extensive procedural details, emphasizing the levitical singers, the proper slaughter arrangements, and the exact correspondence to Moses' prescription — all amplifying the 2 Kings account's claim that this Passover was done 'as it is written.'\n\nVerse 24 functions as a summary of everything the reform accomplished, including the removal of mediums, spiritists, teraphim, and idols. But the motive clause is the verse's theological contribution: 'that he might confirm (*qum*, to cause to stand, to establish) the words of the law written in the book.' Josiah is not originating policy; he is establishing pre-existing divine policy. The reform's authority is entirely derivative — it stands or falls with the authority of the book found in the temple.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pesach* — Passover, from the verb *pasach* (to pass over, spare), commemorating the death-angel's passing over the blood-marked doorways in Egypt (Exodus 12:13). *Qamay* / *qum* (to confirm, establish) — to cause to stand; Josiah's acts cause the already-written words to stand in historical reality. The verb implies the law's prior authority independent of his obedience."
      },
      {
        "number": 4,
        "title": "The unmatched king and the undiminished wrath — the chapter's theological crisis",
        "range": "23:25-27",
        "excerpt": "Before him there was no king like him who turned to the LORD with all his heart... nor did any like him arise after him. However, the LORD did not turn from the fierceness of His great wrath with which His anger burned against Judah.",
        "body": "Three verses carry the weight of the entire chapter's theology, and they are structured to collide. Verse 25 is the Deuteronomistic historian's highest possible praise: measured against the full standard of the law of Moses, with the Shema's triple demand of heart, soul, and might, no king before or after Josiah reached this benchmark. The narrator is not being hyperbolic — he has graded every king in 1-2 Kings against the Deuteronomic standard, and Josiah alone receives the unqualified superlative. Even David, the standard of comparison for all other kings (1 Kings 11:4; 14:8), is not credited with this particular achievement in these terms.\n\nThen verse 26 begins with *akh* — 'however,' 'nevertheless,' 'but only.' This adversative particle is the Old Testament's signal that what follows will qualify or contradict what precedes. The LORD did not turn from His fierce wrath against Judah 'because of all the provocations with which Manasseh had provoked Him.' The verb 'turn' (*shuv*) is the same root used for Josiah's turning to the LORD in verse 25. Josiah turned (*shuv*) to the LORD. The LORD did not turn (*shuv*) from His wrath. The wordplay is deliberate and the asymmetry is devastating: one man's maximal covenantal obedience cannot produce a divine reversal of judgment decreed against a whole nation's accumulated apostasy.\n\nThe theological question this raises has exercised commentators across centuries. John Calvin argued that God's judicial decisions regarding national judgment operate on a different register than His forgiveness of individual sin — the covenant's penal sanctions for corporate apostasy have an objective weight that individual, even royal, repentance cannot simply negate. The nation had passed a threshold in Manasseh's reign (2 Kings 21:12-15) where the LORD had explicitly announced irreversible judgment. Josiah's reform secured a postponement (2 Kings 22:19-20) — Josiah himself would not see the disaster — but not a cancellation. This reading aligns with Jeremiah's prophetic ministry, which ran concurrently with Josiah's reign: even as Josiah reformed externally, Jeremiah announced that the people's hearts were unchanged (Jeremiah 3:10 — 'Judah did not return to Me with her whole heart, but only in pretense') and that a new covenant was needed that could accomplish what no external reform could (Jeremiah 31:31-34).\n\nVerse 27 announces the verdict in the divine first person: 'I will remove Judah also from My sight, as I have removed Israel.' The parallel to the northern exile is precise and intentional. God had removed Israel (722 BC) for the same categories of sin; now the southern kingdom will follow the same trajectory. The city He chose (Jerusalem) and the temple where His name dwelt — both will be abandoned by His protective presence. The irony is total: the most faithful king in Judah's history presides over the generation that receives the final notice of divine abandonment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shuv* (turn, return) — the key root for both Josiah's turning to God (v.25) and the LORD's non-turning of wrath (v.26); the word-play makes the theological tension structural. *Charon aph* (fierce anger, burning nose) — the strongest OT idiom for divine wrath; *aph* is literally 'nostril/nose,' the physical expression of panting rage. *Sur* (remove, take away) — to turn aside, to cause to depart; God is the active agent of Judah's coming exile."
      },
      {
        "number": 5,
        "title": "Death at Megiddo and the rapid succession — reform without transformation",
        "range": "23:28-37",
        "excerpt": "And King Josiah went to meet him, and when Pharaoh Neco saw him he killed him at Megiddo... He did evil in the sight of the LORD, according to all that his fathers had done.",
        "body": "The final ten verses of the chapter form the reform's political epilogue, and they are structured as a controlled descent. Josiah's death at Megiddo (23:29-30) is narrated with the same economy that characterized the great Davidic kings' death notices — there is no battle narrative, no final speech, no divine word explaining the outcome. The Chronicler adds the detail that Neco warned Josiah he was not Josiah's adversary (2 Chronicles 35:21) — the implication being that Josiah's intervention was not divinely authorized and that he died for a military miscalculation, not for his faith. The 2 Kings account preserves the silence, and the silence is the message: the man who did everything right died at Megiddo, and the narrator offers no theodicy.\n\nThe rapid succession that follows inverts every gain of the reform. Jehoahaz, anointed by the people (23:30), was deposed by Egypt in three months and died in Egyptian captivity (23:34) — Pharaoh's puppet economy replacing Josiah's covenant community in a single administrative season. Jehoiakim, installed and renamed by Neco (23:34), taxed the people to pay Egyptian tribute (23:35) — the land's surplus now flowing to Pharaoh rather than funding temple worship. Both kings 'did evil in the sight of the LORD according to all that his fathers had done' (23:32, 37). The formula is unvaried. The reform produced no successor who shared Josiah's heart.\n\nThis is the deepest practical failure of the Mosaic covenant as a reform mechanism: it could regulate behavior, even produce extraordinary behavioral conformity in a king like Josiah, but it could not create what the prophets called a 'new heart' (Ezekiel 36:26). John Owen's theological insight is relevant here: external reformation deals with the acts of sin but not the principle of sin; only regeneration addresses the root. The Deuteronomistic historian seems to grasp this intuitively — by placing the superlative verdict of verse 25 immediately before the divine judgment announcement of verse 26, and then narrating the reform's institutional collapse in verses 28-37, he is composing a sustained argument that something beyond the Mosaic covenant is required.\n\nThe renaming of Eliakim to Jehoiakim by Pharaoh (23:34) carries symbolic weight that the original audience would have heard immediately. In the ancient Near East, renaming was an act of sovereignty — the one who names owns the one named (cf. Daniel 1:7, where Nebuchadnezzar renamed the Judean exiles). That an Egyptian pharaoh is assigning throne names to Davidic heirs signals that the covenant line of David has become an imperial instrumentality. The promises made to David (2 Samuel 7:12-16) are not forgotten by the narrator — but their fulfillment is now suspended in a way that no human restoration of the Mosaic covenant can address. The chapter ends, and Judah waits for Babylon.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mut* (die, kill) — used three times in the chapter's closing section (23:29, 30, 34) for Josiah killed, his body carried, and Jehoahaz dying in Egypt; the repetition creates a cadence of death that closes the reform era. *Malakh* (to become king, to reign) — the standard regnal verb; its rapid alternation across vv.30-36 (Jehoahaz, then Jehoiakim) enacts linguistically the instability of succession. *Ra'ah be'einei YHWH* (did evil in the eyes of the LORD) — the standard negative regnal formula, now appearing twice in quick succession after the long absence of that formula during Josiah's reign."
      }
